10 82   GLOUCESTER. Now is the winter of our discontent
10 83     Made glorious summer by this sun of York;
10 84     And all the clouds that lour'd upon our house
10 85     In the deep bosom of the ocean buried.
10 86     Now are our brows bound with victorious wreaths;
10 87     Our bruised arms hung up for monuments;
10 88     Our stern alarums chang'd to merry meetings,
10 89     Our dreadful marches to delightful measures.
10 90     Grim-visag'd war hath smooth'd his wrinkled front,
10 91     And now, instead of mounting barbed steeds
10 92     To fright the souls of fearful adversaries,
10 93     He capers nimbly in a lady's chamber
10 94     To the lascivious pleasing of a lute.
10 95     But I-that am not shap'd for sportive tricks,
10 96     Nor made to court an amorous looking-glass-
10 97     I-that am rudely stamp'd, and want love's majesty
10 98     To strut before a wanton ambling nymph-
10 99     I-that am curtail'd of this fair proportion,
10 100     Cheated of feature by dissembling nature,
10 101     Deform'd, unfinish'd, sent before my time
10 102     Into this breathing world scarce half made up,
10 103     And that so lamely and unfashionable
10 104     That dogs bark at me as I halt by them-
10 105     Why, I, in this weak piping time of peace,
10 106     Have no delight to pass away the time,
10 107     Unless to spy my shadow in the sun
10 108     And descant on mine own deformity.
10 109     And therefore, since I cannot prove a lover
10 110     To entertain these fair well-spoken days,
10 111     I am determined to prove a villain
10 112     And hate the idle pleasures of these days.
10 113     Plots have I laid, inductions dangerous,
10 114     By drunken prophecies, libels, and dreams,
10 115     To set my brother Clarence and the King
10 116     In deadly hate the one against the other;
10 117     And if King Edward be as true and just
10 118     As I am subtle, false, and treacherous,
10 119     This day should Clarence closely be mew'd up-
10 120     About a prophecy which says that G
10 121     Of Edward's heirs the murderer shall be.
10 122     Dive, thoughts, down to my soul. Here Clarence comes.
