10 528     Having God, her conscience, and these bars against me,
10 529     And I no friends to back my suit at all
10 530     But the plain devil and dissembling looks,
10 531     And yet to win her, all the world to nothing!
10 532     Ha!
10 533     Hath she forgot already that brave prince,
10 534     Edward, her lord, whom I, some three months since,
10 535     Stabb'd in my angry mood at Tewksbury?
10 536     A sweeter and a lovelier gentleman-
10 537     Fram'd in the prodigality of nature,
10 538     Young, valiant, wise, and no doubt right royal-
10 539     The spacious world cannot again afford;
10 540     And will she yet abase her eyes on me,
10 541     That cropp'd the golden prime of this sweet prince
10 542     And made her widow to a woeful bed?
10 543     On me, whose all not equals Edward's moiety?
