10 4513     Wear it, enjoy it, and make much of it.
10 4514   RICHMOND. Great God of heaven, say Amen to all!
10 4515     But, teLL me is young George Stanley living.
10 4516   DERBY. He is, my lord, and safe in Leicester town,
10 4517     Whither, if it please you, we may now withdraw us.
10 4518   RICHMOND. What men of name are slain on either side?
10 4519   DERBY. John Duke of Norfolk, Walter Lord Ferrers,
10 4520     Sir Robert Brakenbury, and Sir William Brandon.
10 4521   RICHMOND. Inter their bodies as becomes their births.
10 4522     Proclaim a pardon to the soldiers fled
10 4523     That in submission will return to us.
10 4524     And then, as we have ta'en the sacrament,
10 4525     We will unite the white rose and the red.
10 4526     Smile heaven upon this fair conjunction,
10 4527     That long have frown'd upon their emnity!
10 4528     What traitor hears me, and says not Amen?
10 4529     England hath long been mad, and scarr'd herself;
10 4530     The brother blindly shed the brother's blood,
10 4531     The father rashly slaughter'd his own son,
10 4532     The son, compell'd, been butcher to the sire;
10 4533     All this divided York and Lancaster,
10 4534     Divided in their dire division,
10 4535     O, now let Richmond and Elizabeth,
10 4536     The true succeeders of each royal house,
10 4537     By God's fair ordinance conjoin together!
10 4538     And let their heirs, God, if thy will be so,
10 4539     Enrich the time to come with smooth-fac'd peace,
10 4540     With smiling plenty, and fair prosperous days!
10 4541     Abate the edge of traitors, gracious Lord,
10 4542     That would reduce these bloody days again
10 4543     And make poor England weep in streams of blood!
10 4544     Let them not live to taste this land's increase
10 4545     That would with treason wound this fair land's peace!
10 4546     Now civil wounds are stopp'd, peace lives again-
10 4547     That she may long live here, God say Amen!            Exeunt
